Here are the most frequently asked LINQ questions in C# interviews for 3â€“5 years of experience, especially useful for .NET full-stack or backend developer roles:


---

ğŸ”¹ 1. What is LINQ in C#?

â†’ LINQ stands for Language Integrated Query.
â†’ It lets you write queries directly in C# to filter, sort, group, or transform data from collections (like arrays, lists, DB sets).


---

ğŸ”¹ 2. Difference between Method Syntax and Query Syntax in LINQ?

Great question â€” and it's a very common interview topic!

Hereâ€™s how you can explain the difference between Method Syntax and Query Syntax in LINQ using simple language + code examples, so that it's easy to remember and explain in interviews:


---

âœ… Simple Interview Answer:

In LINQ (Language Integrated Query), we write queries in two ways:

1. Query Syntax â€” Looks like SQL

2. Method Syntax â€” Uses C# methods like .Where(), .Select()

Both give the same result. The difference is in style only.


---

ğŸ”¹ Query Syntax (SQL-like style)

var result = from s in students
             where s.Age > 20
             select s;

Easy to read

Looks like SQL

Good for beginners or simple queries



---

ğŸ”¹ Method Syntax (Fluent method style)

var result = students.Where(s => s.Age > 20);

More powerful

Required for advanced operations (e.g., joins, grouping with conditions)



---

âœ… Sample Data for both examples:

public class Student
{
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public int Age { get; set; }
}

List<Student> students = new List<Student>
{
    new Student { Name = "Abhi", Age = 22 },
    new Student { Name = "Ravi", Age = 19 },
    new Student { Name = "Mona", Age = 25 }
};


---

ğŸ§  Real-world analogy:

Query Syntax = Easy spoken English:
â€œGive me all students where age > 20.â€

Method Syntax = Precise code-like language:
â€œstudents.Where(...).Select(...)â€



---

ğŸ’¡ Interview Summary:

> LINQ gives two ways to write queries:

Query Syntax: looks like SQL, good for basic queries.

Method Syntax: uses C# methods, more flexible and powerful.


âœ… Both are correct â€” you can choose based on your comfort or the query complexity.




